defaultBackground – The “Durban Strategy”default&#xa0;default11.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn August 2001, the UN held the World Conference 
defaultAgainst
default Racism in Durban, South Africa. At the NGO Forum, which ran parallel to the governmental conference, 1,500 non-governmental organizations (NGOs) 
defaultadopted 
defaulta strategy 
defaultof 
defaultsingl
defaulting-
defaultout Israel as a “racist” and “apartheid” state, and isolat
defaulting
default it through campaign 
defaultbased on 
defaultlawfare
default and 
defaultboycotts, divestment, and sanctions.
default 
defaultLawfare
default is the exploitation of legal frameworks to advance the political war against Israel. 
default12.
default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultNGO Durban declaration
default also 
defaultcalled for the “adoption of all measures to ensure [the] enforcement” of international humanitarian law, including “the establishment of a war crimes tribunal to investigate and bring to justice those who may be guilty of war crimes, acts of genocide and ethnic cleansing and the crime of Apartheid . . . perpetrated in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories.”
default13.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn implementing the Durban strategy s
defaultince 200
default1, political advocacy NGOs have exploited courts in democratic countries in order to harass Israeli officials with civil lawsuits and criminal investigations for “war crimes,” “crimes against humanity,” and other alleged violations of international law.
