defaultOverview of DFID Funding to NRCdefault16.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) 
defaultdescribes
default itself as “an independent, humanitarian, non-profit, non-governmental 
defaultorganisation
default which provides assistance, protection and durable solutions to refugees and internally displaced persons worldwide.” Its budget for 
defaultPalestine
default in 2013 alone was 56 million NOK (~£5.5 million), with the bulk coming from governments: the UK, the EU, Norway, and Sweden. 
default17.
default&#xa0; 
defaultBetween December 2010 and March 2013, DFID transferred £2,990,599 to NRC for the “Information, 
defaultCounselling
default and Legal Assistance 
defaultProgramme
default in the Occupied Palestinian 
defaultTerritories.” The 
defaultstated goal
default of this funding is “Improved access to justice in the Occupied Palestinian Territories for refugees, internally displaced persons, and persons/communities at risk of displacement or affected by displacement.”
default18.
default&#xa0; 
defaultNRC is 
defaultcurrently receiving
default an additional £3 million for FY 13/14-14/15 for a seemingly identical project
default,
default “Legal Assistance to prevent displacement and demolitions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs).”
default19.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThese grants are unprecedented in content, scope, and size. NGO Monitor is unaware of similar funding for NGO legal advocacy in the context of another conflict region or another democratic country. 
default20.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK’s Development Tracker website provides a certain level of transparency regarding these grants – including a breakdown of spending in each financial year, as well as 
defaulthighly detailed documents
default on the activities undertaken by NRC 
defaultwith UK funding 
defaultand 
defaulta number of 
defaultDFID evaluation
defaults
default.  
default21.
default&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, there is also a marked lack of transparency regarding NRC’s expenditures. According to the 
defaultDevelopment Tracker
default, £2,890,599 of the first grant was disbursed as “Aid to civil society organizations/NGOs.” Yet, the final recipients of the funds are “withheld” and unidentified. The 
defaultsame language
default is used regarding the single disbursement to date (£189,679) from the second project.  
default22.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTherefore, concerned citizens in the UK and Israel cannot know which organizations are receiving and spending British taxpayer funds. As seen below, NGO Monitor was able to independently reconstruct some of the sub-grants by cross-referencing the partial information provided by DFID with NGO financial statements.
