defaultNRC’s Non-transparent Roledefault&#xa0;
default24.
default&#xa0; 
defaultNRC uses British government funds to provide legal assistance and legal training, as well as “research and advocacy” on alleged “violations of international law by Israel.” This is accomplished, “
defaultin the vast majority of cases
default,” by transferring funds to “local lawyers and NGOs to carry out legal 
defaultcounselling
default and represent cases in court.”
default25.
default&#xa0; 
defaultNRC acknowledges that it engages in “
defaultpolicy change work
default,” consisting of “research and advocacy….through engagement with the diplomatic community and use of international justice mechanisms. NRC will also take on public interest cases that highlight discriminatory laws and practices and will carry out related advocacy on these cases.”
default26.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAccording to the documents available through Development Tracker, NRC engages in a “
defaultlow visibility policy
default,” obscuring its involvement in legal advocacy and political activities. This is “to ensure that their legal status to carry out their work is not threatened” – most likely referring to restrictions 
defaultagainst 
defaultactivities that are not strictly humanitarian
default upon which entry into Israel is conditioned. 
default27.
default&#xa0; 
defaultNGO Monitor repeatedly attempted to contact
default NRC’s representatives in Israel and the Palestinian Authority in order to discuss their activities and learn more about the project. Reflecting the lack of transparency and secrecy regarding the NRC’s activities, however, the organization did not respond. 
defaultScope and Damage of NRC’s Legal Advocacydefault28.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe scope of NRC’s interference in the Israeli legal system is staggering. Among other activities, UK funding financed 677 cases that received “full legal representation at the relevant court/administrative body.” 
default29.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAccording to an 
defaultevaluation conducted in April 2012 and discussed in the 
defaultProject Completion Review
default, NRC is responsible for 51% of all house demolition cases in Area C of the West Bank. According to 
defaultanother assessment
default, the data suggest that 35% of all legal cases dealing with housing, land, and property claims in East Jerusalem and Area C of the West Bank are funded by NRC. 
default30.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAdditionally, NRC has a 
defaultfocus
default on “public interest cases that highlight discriminatory laws and practices and will carry out related advocacy on these cases.” These cases are highly important
default, as “NRC hopes to obtain legal precedents in public interest cases that will likewise increase the pressure to change policy and practice” – in other words, to manipulate the Israeli democratic system. 
default31.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAccording to a 
defaultreport by a Dutch national
default, who attended a presentation by a lawyer apparently affiliated with this NRC program, these cases are an attempt to 
default“try every possible legal measure to disrupt the Israeli judicial system… as many cases as possible are registered and that as many cases as possible are appealed to increase the workload of the courts and the Supreme Court to such an extent that there will be a blockagedefault” (
defaultemphasis added, 
defaulttranslation from original Dutch by NGO Monitor).
